    "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
    "body": "### Problem\n\nThe `cursorline`, `cursorcolumn`, and `colorcolumn` settings seem to do nothing in the new default nvim colorscheme:\r\n\r\n<img width=\"505\" alt=\"Screenshot of nvim open in three colorschemes (default, vim, desert), with line and column highlighted in the latter two but not the first\" src=\"https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/9fdcee40-329a-4d5b-90dd-0a24cc824e00\">\r\n\r\nI quite like the minimalism and contrast of the new scheme overall, but column highlighting is very useful for me for eyeballing whether two pieces of code are at the same indentation level, and line highlighting is useful to draw the eye.\r\n\r\nTested latest release as well as nightly gadef830f8. Using macOS default Terminal.app. Also tested in different Terminal.app color schemes and couldn't find anything that worked.\r\n\n\n### Steps to reproduce\n\n```\r\nnvim --clean +':set cursorline cursorcolumn colorcolumn=+1' +':norm 5Oxxxxx' +':norm 3G0ll'\r\n```\r\n\r\nThen `:colorscheme vim` and note the difference.\n\n### Expected behavior\n\nThe current line is underlined or highlighted in some way, as is the current column.\n\n### Neovim version (nvim -v)\n\nv0.10.0, v0.11.0-dev-470+gadef830f8\n\n### Vim (not Nvim) behaves the same?\n\nno (N/A)\n\n### Operating system/version\n\nmacOS Sonoma 14.5\n\n### Terminal name/version\n\nApple Terminal 2.14 (453)\n\n### $TERM environment variable\n\nxterm-256color\n\n### Installation\n\nGitHub releases, nvim-macos-arm64",
    "closed_at": "2024-07-19T18:42:23Z",
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Don't use Apple Terminal, it's broken. (You need `:termguicolors` for the best experience, otherwise there's just not enough different colors to waste on the columns.)",
